## The browser side - Stripe.js and Elements

Stripe provides a JavaScript library called **Stripe.js** that renders a secure card input form directly in your page. The input is in an iframe hosted by Stripe, so card numbers never touch your server.

Add a route that serves an HTML checkout page:

```python
from fastapi.responses import HTMLResponse

@app.get('/checkout', response_class=HTMLResponse)
def checkout_page():
    return f"""
    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html>
    <head>
      <script src="https://js.stripe.com/v3/"></script>
    </head>
    <body>
      <h1>Checkout</h1>
      <div id="payment-element"></div>
      <button id="pay">Pay $9.99</button>
      <div id="message"></div>
      <script>
        const stripe = Stripe('{STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY}');

        // 1. Create a payment intent
        fetch('/create-payment-intent', {{
          method: 'POST',
          headers: {{'Content-Type': 'application/json'}},
          body: JSON.stringify({{amount_cents: 999, description: 'Coffee'}})
        }})
        .then(r => r.json())
        .then(data => {{
          // 2. Mount the Stripe payment form
          const elements = stripe.elements({{clientSecret: data.client_secret}});
          const paymentElement = elements.create('payment');
          paymentElement.mount('#payment-element');

          // 3. On click, confirm the payment
          document.getElementById('pay').addEventListener('click', async () => {{
            const result = await stripe.confirmPayment({{
              elements,
              confirmParams: {{return_url: 'http://localhost:8000/success'}}
            }});
            if (result.error) {{
              document.getElementById('message').textContent = result.error.message;
            }}
          }});
        }});
      </script>
    </body>
    </html>
    """
```

Note the double curly braces `{{` and `}}` inside the f-string - in Python f-strings, `{{` is how you write a literal `{` without it being treated as a variable.

Add the checkout page route and a simple `GET /success` route that returns `'Payment successful!'`.

